Republican Party strategy against Obama re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies on the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center calls such fraud a myth, saying that voter fraud is less common in the U.S. than the number of people who die from lightning strikes.
In fact, Republican advocates have only seen 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in the past decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, individual states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And in this spirit, most U.S. governments since 2009 have enacted new laws that make it difficult to vote or register.
This was followed by the November 2010 election, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting voting rights in 41 states were tabled in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to present photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws limit the period for elections in advance, invalidate the right to register on the electoral roll on the day of the election, and revoke the right to vote for citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to submit a photo ID.
The first state to introduce this requirement was Indiana.
The constitutionality of the Indian law was upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court in 2008.
Republican authorities rushed to expand this procedure to other states as well.
Over the past two years, they have backed bills like this in 34 states to force voters to present photo IDs.
It should be noted that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card, such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, or 21 million voting age citizens, do not own a photo ID issued by their state government.
Furthermore, about five million new voters do not have such an identity card in 2012.
In addition, acquiring the required identity card often costs more than a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people on low incomes.
Therefore, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with an income below $35,000; 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID.
And that's not all.
Students who are known as voters for their attachment to Democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their school in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of hunting or fishing clubs who elect rather Republican candidates to use cards issued by these clubs in elections.
Until 2004, no state required proof of citizenship for elections.
The first such request was made by Arizona.
As of 2011, about a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the number of votes cast by the Hispanic minority.
It should be noted that two out of three Hispanics prefer the Democratic Party.
In 2011, Republican lawmakers in eight states backed legislation that scraps voter registration on election day.
They also restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to enrol.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, during the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped register about 10 million inhabitants.
However, measures taken after 2009 caused a 17% decrease in the number of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
Republican lawmakers in five other states passed laws aimed at shortening the term for elections in advance.
For example, during the 2008 Florida general election, African-Americans made up 33% of the electorate that voted in advance, even though the African-American electorate in that state was only 13%.
It was the same with Hispanics.
They made up only 11% of all voters, but 24% of citizens voting in advance.
On the other hand, whites, who made up 76% of all voters, made up just 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have strongly opposed passing laws that restrict voter registration.
Democratic governors blocked several bills with their vetoes.
In order to suspend the most controversial laws, even the Attorney General of the United States intervened.
The damage was partially reduced.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the submission of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult in 2012.
Democratic critics mainly speak of the bias of the approved laws and see them as an apparent effort to influence the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that states where these laws have been passed account for 171 of the 270 electoral votes necessary to win the presidential election.
It is too early to state with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, these measures will partially undermine the American democratic system.
Detection of prostate cancer: to undergo an examination or not?
The PSA test sometimes produced erroneous results that were wrongly negative or even wrongly positive, leading to unnecessary medical interventions.
All this increased the hesitation of men who were already reluctant to go to the examination at all.
To be examined or not?
We asked for the opinion of two experts.
Studies conducted in the USA showed a high level of contamination among the individual test groups, so it is difficult to interpret these results and bring valuable recommendations.
Another study, this time a European one, found a difference in mortality between patients who underwent the test and those who did not.
This study also showed that those who did not undergo the test had a 30-40% higher risk of metastases.
Therefore, I recommend screening from the age of 50 or 40 if your immediate relative has had prostate cancer.
Men of African American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is detected.
There are aggressive types of cancer and those that are inert.
It is therefore necessary to correctly explain to the patient the degree of danger of his type of cancer, to offer him possible alternatives, not necessarily to treat prostate cancer, which does not affect life in the long term, and to focus in these cases on active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who have been diagnosed with cancer are left untreated because their cancer is not aggressive or life-threatening.
Rather, we will suggest active surveillance and offer treatment in the event of disease progression.
Increasingly, and with greater precision, we are setting criteria that help in deciding which species to treat and which not.
Nevertheless, I recommend that you take the test.
However, it is important to consult a doctor and determine whether it is appropriate to undergo an examination or not.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has created a tool to evaluate the pros and cons of PSA testing.
You can download this document (currently in English, translation will be available later) at the following address: http://ca.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Disease prevention
Unfortunately, there is no magic formula for cancer prevention.
