the Higgs Boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a justified stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all matter in the universe.
And this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
However, there is still no certainty among physicists that it is a Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle that closely resembles the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
The new data released this week at the Big Physical Congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but all the data is still missing to give us absolute certainty.
However, suppose it is a Higgs boson, since the risks of error appear small, and let's see what it is all about.
In this world, there is an unquestionable law according to which two things cannot occur in the same place at the same time.
This rule can not be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies: the Pauli exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly creates some of their properties.
Physics particles are divided into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow the Pauli principle.
And at the other end there are bosons, wicked anarchists, who value nothing at all - certainly not this principle, which means that they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the device (absolutely amazing, by the way) which is The Particle Adventure, in the Berkeley laboratories: mesons, which we will leave unnoticed here, and the "force particles" with which the great forces of nature spread, and with which the Higgs boson is probably somehow related.
But it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic as one might think.
If you read this article, it’s thanks to a boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or “particle of light,” that is the “carrier” of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field in this particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "interference" produces an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and thus one of the bosons, "carriers of force".
A more stable field
It is also the case with the Higgs boson, except that it takes a different field, the Higgs field, to "disturb" it.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to achieve very high energy values, similar to the frozen surface of a pond, only a very large boulder will rain.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator of a part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with accommodating beams is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to clarify the relationship between Higgs and matter.
Neither all particles nor all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, for example, magnets, do so, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never keep itself on the refrigerator.
And equally, with the Higgs field, not all particles react: those that do have a certain mass, while others (such as a photon, let's look at it) don't.
And Mrs. Novak asks what all this research is for, what will it "bring to us"?
From a scientific point of view, this confirms the validity of the Standard Model (SM), allowing physicists to examine any mismatch between the observations and predictions of SM.
Moreover, not a few physicists literally want to be able to find them, because the slightest difference could open up the space of "new physics" and close some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge flaws, does not bring any clarification of gravity (haha!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the universe's matter (again ouha!).
Until now, however, CERN has not found such contradictions.
Responses
It is difficult to predict the response of this research in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. Novak, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
See: in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers at Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work would spark.
They assumed scientific use, but nothing else.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first permanent laser beam (previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I have already said this - the laser was initially considered such a "toy to the lab".
Just imagine...
In addition, the application can also result from all the tools that surround the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle created a small light sensor in 1969 during his work on optics.
This sensor, although Boyle did not initially plan to do so, now serves as the "eye" of all digital cameras in the world and earned him the Nobel Prize for Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities around the LHC necessarily have to change our lives, but it does mean that one really never knows...
Palliative Care: The Best Way to Leave Life by Le Devoir
Through his Commission for the Dignity of Dying, Quebec has recently engaged in a delicate end-of-life question.
The debate is expected to continue soon, and a bill is being drafted.
There is still a lot of work to be done in this crucial area.
The magazine Le Devoir tried to look at this issue in more detail.
Less than a few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him gave him a two-year reprieve.
“They gave me five years to live, and it’s now seven,” he says on his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the previous day.
"It's still a shock, you can't prepare for this," he adds.
The disease has done its job: immense weakness makes it impossible for him to go to the toilet alone or to eat alone.
He looks down on a delicious-looking breakfast and agrees to help him eat.
He is courageous and even smiles, talking to strangers who stop by, bring him medicine, offer him a bath.
The courage of a simple death.
"My biggest wish is to get rid of the diarrhea, it demeans me," he confides.
A few hours later, a team of doctors found a cure for his problem.
“Throughout life, a man learns that men urinate standing up,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois facility.
Returning to the child stage is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the abilities of each person" whether he accepts the return, the psychologist claims.
In the opinion of many palliative care professionals, crucial moments take place at the very heart of such a return.
Patients who enter the home with palliative care Victor-Gadbois, all suffer from cancer.
Their prognosis is a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses who care for them does not provide so-called "medical" care.
In the case of Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "from asphyxiation while fully conscious".
Illness has allowed me to discover my children.
“I have good children,” he adds.
“I don’t have any more wishes in my life,” she says, and then she agrees to put on her breathing apparatus.
He is looking forward to his last visit to Italy in the coming days.
At the Victor-Gadbois home, nutrition care is provided in collaboration with a group of volunteers.
This is what palliative care looks like when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for every 11,700 people.
That's very little if we realize that we're all going to die.
Here, life continues in optimal conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the home.
Whether it is a level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
When a person dies, for example, he can be given a sip of brandy or pepsi, to taste.
Diabetics no longer need to monitor their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night they brought beer to Mr. X, who died later that night.
This morning, his son will finish his beer in honor of his late father.
“We help patients as well as their loved ones,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care services.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, days go by, but they don't resemble each other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who rejoices in his last encounter with his family thoroughly cushioned while being toasted in his honor, a 36-year-old man tragically dies surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children after trying every possible way to survive.
“For half a year, there are always three to five beds that are designed for people with cancer under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients who come to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% come from hospitals.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care that is intended to alleviate suffering once the sick person reaches the final stage of his or her life, whether it be at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home of Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Treatment of the Grand Montréal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care provided to cancer patients.
And it is this fundamental inaccessibility of healthcare in Quebec that has led many palliative care doctors to fear the passage of a law on euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation signed by palliative treatment leaders such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in which they demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has access to quality palliative care before euthanasia can be approved.
She says she recently experienced a patient who spent 14 days in the E.R. in tremendous pain without anyone taking the necessary steps to relieve her.
They are concerned that patients should not be asked to die because they are not receiving proper care.
And at the same time, many oncologists take care of their patients until the last moments, regardless of the unfavorable prognosis.
Hopes for the survival of Helene Richard were already very low when she left her demanding chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was quitting treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she told us.
And she told me it was over!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their treating physicians for not fulfilling their wishes when the palliative cunt team eased their pain.
Palliative care is not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, patients resist pain management in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives, which put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either intermittently or permanently.
We cannot pretend that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient who is not relieved of pain will have greater and greater access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: "I want to die".
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want you to get rid of my pain.”
