How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users takes place between two e-mail addresses.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thereby ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
Thus, the network can verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in the public ledger of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key stage is to write this new transaction into this book.
It is done by solving a mathematical task given to computers, whose solver, a temporary central banker, will have the right to write this additional line.
This is the cutting-out phase of a file; that is, the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital imprint.
Computers "take" this new transaction and add a number to it, only then "slash" the whole.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific imprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes will easily check its correctness.
The transaction will then appear indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wanted to pay twice the same money for the purpose of fraud very quickly (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each of them has a different fingerprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided by two, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided into one hundred millionths, so there is room for margin.
The difficulty of the specified task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and stolen bitcoins stored there.
“The loophole used is not about the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also controls the possibility of money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Prominent players like Wikipedia refuse gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the ledger of current accounts and proved that almost 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "huge discounts" were launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, a Bitcoin-to-Gold company.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
His system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless mobile payment, but uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions, which makes them cheaper.
In addition, the bearer manages his/her identity and can remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up with traders, where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
Just give an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by the phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems and move towards more horizontal systems.
“Bitcoin will take a while to establish itself, but 2013 could be a decisive year,” he said.
Moreover, the ECB’s report envisages a reassessment of the various risks that are now considered to be increased if this type of money is successful.
