Difficult work on the Egyptian Constitution
President Mohamed Morsi is playing another round of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the promulgation of a constitution temporarily granting it unlimited powers, it decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, regardless of everyone else's opinion, he announced that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text the next day.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has used a provisional text that has been amended many times, which weakens the country's constitutional stability and leads to legal conjecture.
This new initiative only further strengthened the country's ambivalence.
From the opposition's point of view, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium", continues to "break his word" and "steps the law".
But his supporters say it is a means to tackle the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum will be held in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of the text to the Egyptians to clarify the article by article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy, while protests are raging across the country.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems confident that the Egyptians will vote in favour.
Especially because this hastily organised vote puts the Egyptian people before an ultimatum: 'You will either approve my text or I will retain unlimited powers', which should otherwise come to an end when the new constitution is approved.
And in this strange atmosphere, yesterday 85 deputies of the above-mentioned Constituent Assembly with a large majority of Islamists approved the text.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the declaration of the constitution, they slammed the door, saying they had no opportunity to assert their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities have imitated their step.
In order to reach a quorum, 11 alternates were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising, then, that the articles of the Constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further paused on the fact that one of the few controversies that day revolved around... hours of prayer, when some members of the committee held the view that the hours in the boardroom were not properly arranged.
The text that was voted on last night consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains consistent with the 1971 version of the Constitution, stating that "the principles of sharia law are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the crucial requirements, hoped to replace the term "principles" with the term "rules", which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that the article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," objected the liberals, who see it only as a rhetorical problem.
Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which confers an advisory role on al-Azhar University, in particular for issues of checking the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "persons called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This is the beginning of a theocracy.”
Liberals are even more alarmed by the fact that the university’s next rector should be less moderate than the current one.
"So far, there has been no concrete religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulamas, but university workers, many of whom have graduated from French schools," Alexis Blouet, who is preparing work on the constitutional transition in Egypt, said in a statement.
However, he agrees that "there may be discrepancies over the interpretation of Article 220 because the terms used in it belong to a religious dictionary.
There is especially a reference to "fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question may arise of the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on this.”
The text approved yesterday is highly criticized in addition to religious sites because of the extended powers granted to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that they have been severely curtailed compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: powers vested in the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the representatives of the military, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, civilian trials will not be prohibited in military courts, as requested by the human rights association.
These associations speak of their doubts in connection with the text, which they believe is directed against freedom.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and the insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article deals with the protection of women, Human Rights Watch’s Heba Morayef points out.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture referred to in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to make a televised speech last night, rallies are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then manifest on Saturday.
In Israel waiting for Ukrainian tourists holy places, the navel of the world and the sea from saturated salt solution
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of biblical truth, modern comfort, and unspoiled nature.
AaF has identified five of the most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Adoration of the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that God’s mercy will descend upon all who enter this “bath.”
And Galilee - the place of Jesus' miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here, too, Jesus appeared to his disciples and after the resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers will pass through the Way of Pain, or the Way of Jesus of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
It begins at the fortress of Antonia - Pretoria - where the judgment was held, passes through the streets of the Old Town and leads to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Mount Golgotha - the place of crucifixion, the stone of the anointing and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew from which they made a cross for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place for the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the rest of the temple, which was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Take a trip around the vertical
The ruins of Masada remained hidden from the enemy that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 BC.
The ruins are located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who are involved in mountaineering can reach it.
Others will take the cable car to this historic mountain.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous ski resort Hermon, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus transports tourists to this ski paradise from the foot of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to ancient legend, pagan gods lived on top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can’t visit all of them in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as some 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
In his exhibition are widely represented impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso.
In Akkon you can visit the Al Basha Spa Museum, which presents visitors with several rooms of ancient Turkish baths with figurines of bath users and spa attendants from that time.
In Caesarea, the unique private Ralli Museum is worth a visit, where you can admire the statues of Dalí and Rodeno.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly refused.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children's Memorial - was built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You step inside - and you find yourself in total darkness.
The stars twinkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also included.
Improve your health
Israel’s three main spa resorts are located on the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Sea coasts.
Each of them offers swimming pools, aquaparks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
It is interesting that in the Red Sea you can bathe even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air is heated up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even hotter, and people bathe in it all year round.
By the way, the Dead Sea is the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest point on the planet - at 417 m below sea level.
Cyan water in it is a saturated saline solution that easily keeps even people who can not swim.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Head here to undergo treatment using brine, and medicinal mud that can treat health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to heal your ragged nerves.
Touch the Mysterious Past
It is protected by an ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through them passed the famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which they then lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love wandering through the narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
They say that if you cling to the walls in the alley "your" sign, happiness will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even from other countries to get their pictures taken.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully renovated theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, a word
If you are going to Israel, you do not have to worry about your imperfect English: in this country, about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For the journey, it is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now $1 is approximately 3.8 shekels).
Buses are mainly used for public transport, but there is a high-speed tram in Jerusalem, and Haifa is the only metro line in the country with six stations connecting the lower city with the upper one.
Basically, it's an underground cableway.
Travelling by all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can travel 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, Shabbat is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, you stop working in markets, shops and public transport.
And on Sunday morning, the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, you will only get kosher dishes: with the exception of pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes in which milk and meat combinations are included.
They offer a large selection of dishes from lamb and beef, soups and desserts made from coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus, various kinds of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many fat cats who are gracefully "wandering according to their taste".
In the evening you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Ahead cats love crowded places and are eager to embark on any goodies.
Renting a car will cost between $37 a day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 a day (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - 15 dollars a day.
And renting a bike will cost around 15 shekels per day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed by numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
To get to know the country and relax came the most citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
The Promised Land was visited by 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Big and mighty" announce it to Moscow: emigrants will save money on language
While lawmakers and human rights defenders are still debating the law on compulsory language tests, fraudsters have already appeared in the country selling "counterfeit" certificates
Every year, 13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make enough money to support families at home.
On December 1, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to pass a Russian language test.
So far, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing and municipal economy, lifestyle and retail sectors.
However, the FMS promises that, over time, the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the foundations of law.
Language skills will also need to be validated to obtain and extend a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law is not subject to people who successfully achieved attestation and obtained an academic diploma until the dissolution of the USSR in 1991.
Usefulness, Conviction and Protection of Rights
The network of test sites will work under the auspices of Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, University of Friendship between Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; already today, more than 160 such centers are open in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by members of the State Duma and the FMS (Federal Migration Service).
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders were able to put the question in the press many times: and what will it actually bring?
What changes the obligation to know the language for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
First of all - according to representatives of the migration service - this will make it possible to reduce the number of people suffering as a result of "slavery work."
Many people today talk about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, Chairman of the Board of the FMS of Russia in Tajikistan.
Their rights should be protected before they leave.
Only a system of organized recruitment will allow 90% of the problems of foreign workers to be solved.
Problems arise with emigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without the knowledge of the language, he says, the future migrant is doomed to clash with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "voucher" to the horrible, tight lodgings in which he and dozens of others like him will languish for months without food and documents and toil for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrant workers.
"In their homeland, they promise them one thing, but when they arrive, they are tricked, their passports are confiscated, they do not pay the promised wages," said Tolib Sharipov, head of the Main Tajik Labour Migration Administration.
Don't swear!
All the more so since many citizens of Central Asian republics who intend to go to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to get to, but do not even have experience with the given job.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as it is their misfortune: very few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive at least adequate basic education.
After all, their families also need something to feed their children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly dressed, put on and equipped for school.
As children reach working age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without the knowledge of the language, it is difficult - they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
It is true that, with regard to the Law on Language Examinations, human rights defenders point to one important point.
Testing will only be carried out on migrants with legal status.
If they don't, they won't take exams or get any more official jobs.
Meanwhile, the majority of migrant workers are living in Russia illegally.
"Welcome, or Unauthorized Entry"
Many of the incoming workers claim that obtaining official status in our country is not easy.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all the language difficulties.
Legalization, in addition, costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But fake registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that we have basically fake documents, without registration, and there are extortion cases.
"They require a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea," - shared with journalists his experience citizen of Tajikistan Umed Khushkadamov.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the law on language, it was found that fake documents were not just for migrants to register.
The FMS staff has already seized several false certificates of passing the language exam.
Counterfeit documents are printed on an ordinary color printer.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, hoping to ease the problem of passing tests, paid seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more than passing the official test: it will cost migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task of the near future is thus to secure the system from corruption so that workers cannot simply buy documents, government officials and human rights defenders agree.
Meanwhile, government authorities can promise foreign workers who failed the test for the first time the time they need to complete a course on the basics of the Russian language.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas where active interaction with people is not required.
