As for the domestic legislation, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean for your office, are its impacts already being reflected in any way?
Since the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it is not yet reflected in our control actions.
Because we do ex-post checks, we need to anticipate a certain delay.
So far, we are only observing this in the process of preparing future inspections - we have started our new tool "risk detection of inefficiency", through which we have swept almost 14,000 public contracts, and we have analyzed them - there, of course, the changes will be reflected, because the limits will change, the conditions of some types of tender will be adjusted, and so on.
Do you consider the approval of this law to be a benefit or an additional burden on the system of bureaucracy?
I think this law is certainly a step in the right direction, and I hope that will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise here is that the rules will be "tightened" and it will not be possible to comply with them.
Already under the operation of the previous rules, the audited persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes, by the regional council) that any failure to comply with the Public Procurement Act constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth tightening the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who commit formal misconduct that has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only put more pressure on bureaucracy.
So how do we get out of this?
Let's see where the road leads.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that ODS will not bother entrepreneurs with checks on the so-called "svarcsystem" - and what does this mean?
Is the Švarcsystem banned or allowed?
The law must be set up somehow, and if it bans something, then even the Prime Minister can not prevent the operation of the office, which is obliged to go to check and enforce obligations.
He can say, "We'll change the law and allow it," but he can't say that we're going to act like nothing.
There are quite strict rules in the Public Procurement Act on what is to be formally done - which is right to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the candidate with the best offer is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be right - that is what I think is missing in us.
