Šimon Ornest: We want to accumulate positive energy at concerts
What do you think about the end of the world in less than a month?
It's just one of the other alarm messages that we humans like to catch up on.
Together with The Tap Tap, we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also organize a completely unique project three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce it to readers?
It's a national fundraiser we've been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar announced on December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
On the day before, 20 December at 9 pm, 3 concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end around the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific, which is 12 hours ahead of us.
Who came up with this idea?
Originally it was probably my idea, then we invented everything together with our artist Honza Augusta.
In addition to amassing enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, we also want to reflect with the public on the state in which we will one day pass this world on to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we also created a unique collection of items shoes, T-shirts, bags or original keys against the end of the world, which people can also support us by purchasing on www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap, along with other artists, also performed the so-called anthem against the end of the world, which is called "The End of the World Cancelled".
It is already very popular on YouTube, will it also be heard at these benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, that is, if we succeed and the world does not end...
It will be sung by all the performers at all three concerts simultaneously.
The anthems are also connected in a unique live broadcast on Czech Television.
He wrote the words to this song and the main role of Jesus in the clip is played by Tomáš Hanák, in it he also sings Xindl X...
How did you get to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, given that we organize a lot of benefit events and concerts...
We are working hard to get them involved in these projects.
It turns out that most of them are interested in working with us and having fun.
What will the proceeds of the concerts go to against the end of the world?
On the equipment of the barrier-free educational center Studeo, which we have been implementing for the sixth year with the civic association Tap in Jedlička Institute.
The students of Jedlička Institute are regularly attended by lecturers and are engaged in activities that they enjoy and are interested in.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to the lecturers themselves, so we try to allow them to do so in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be built in the future, to which we will move with this project.
Several musical groups and performers will perform at each concert.
How did you choose them?
We tried to create a program that will appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform in Prague.
Full details can be found at www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any such “bombs” in the future?
In May, we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, so we will certainly prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Czech National House in New York, and I personally, while we are in the USA, would like to connect this with the performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not minimalistic, so far you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these routes logistically and organizationally?
It's not as bad as it seems at first glance.
We have five members on an electric wheelchair, its trolleys must travel in the luggage compartment, and of course we carry a large amount of cargo and tool boxes with us...
However, so far it has always been done without any problems, ČSA and British Airways were well prepared for us, that I was surprised how many times.
Even in Moscow, from which we returned recently, it was no problem.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare how different they are in terms of accessibility, public access to the disabled, and so on.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than here, we have just seen in Russia that everything is still in its infancy in the East.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is very barrier-free, here it is still unusual for a person in an electric wheelchair to move alone in the city center.
There is no such thing as a chairlift in the elevator.
Fortunately, there are already civil associations that are trying to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And where do we still have to catch up with more advanced countries?
There's a lot of things we're still behind on...
However, it is important to note that improving and improving the situation is always dependent on the efforts of the people involved.
In London and Madrid it is quite common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public, they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
However, it is not very common for a large number of people with disabilities to take an active part in social life, on the contrary, we are a little ahead of The Tap Tap!
Respecting the public or being barrier-free is one thing, but it’s only when we become great athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers that things really start to change.
So far, these are rare cases of people who have a strong will.
The band The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but let's go back a few years, what made you start it in 1998?
I started as an educator at Jedlička Institute, where I had many young people around me who were interested in doing something.
And since I am a musician myself, I play the saxophone, among other things, so together with a colleague I founded an interest music club.
And over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughs).
But the popularity has come only in recent years, am I wrong?
It was true that it helped us when we started connecting with well-known singers and also actively working on promoting the band.
We realized that work that is not visible, basically, as if it did not exist.
Thanks to contributions from the European Union, we can also afford quality lecturers, equipment and so on.
Was your goal with The Tap Tap this high?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do something different.
Show business is crowded with things where one mimics the other.
It is logical in a way, everything new is taken with care and it takes a long time.
Things that are rare are very few, but I dare say Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person seeing us for the first time is, of course, regret, it's natural...
But that regret is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not suffering from all the abandoned beings that we have to regret.
These are people who can live a full life and develop, provided, of course, that they have the necessary resources to do so.
I say that when people with disabilities succeed, it is not just a shift for them, but for the whole society.
Has being a strict boss, as many people have called you, also helped this success?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many things and require a certain discipline.
I mean, that's perfectly normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic idea and a head in the clouds, and when they find that they have to go to rehearsals twice a week, attend rehearsals, and spend a lot of time traveling to concerts, then the enthusiasm quickly leaves them.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and that wants to achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has 20 members.
How many of them started in 1998?
There is only one Angel.
We are an open group, people are leaving and coming, there is no way to prevent that.
Who has the will and taste, always has the door open to us
