Poland and the Cosmos.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency at the European Space Agency’s Ministerial Meeting, the second country from the former Eastern Bloc countries (after the Czech Republic, which became a full ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of projects of the Agency.
But Poland’s journey into space began much earlier.
Before World War II, Polish enthusiasts had been involved in spaceflight; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Entering Space.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prizes for Entering Space in France.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and has written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was also appreciated for the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railcar was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket should have been used to start or brake the train.
Information about this dressage is known only from the period press.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery has been engaged in missile operations.
The research was provided by Komórka Techniki Armaments in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the surviving materials that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, research was interrupted.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozinski, appeared in the professional press, and in the following year the work of Rakiet - torpedo powietrzna and rakietobomb lotnicza by the author Leliwy-Krzywoblocký was published.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) devoted itself to all projects of military use of missile technology, coordinating all the work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ended with the start of the war.
Further work on space appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of Problemy magazine, which includes four more comprehensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with space.
At that time, projects of artificial satellites were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded 1951), and already in the autumn the PTA became a full member.
And in the following year, the first chairman of the PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959) became the deputy chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has significantly contributed to the development of the very successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) weather rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with an altitude of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were launched in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next development was supposed to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high-altitude wind.
In 1962, however, further development was suspended.
The first RM rocket was the Meteor-1, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B, and -1C) were developed, differing in size of space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket was available space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Institute of Aeronautics developed the Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland joined the Committee for Space Research in 1960 and formed a national committee two years later.
Poland also became involved in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not the solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively public debate.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a wider perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU as well as in the globalized world are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In its effect, this means that individual economic formations, national economic systems, are in permanent conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital along with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in labour price, (wage) there is a price tension.
This is to be understood as a situation in which a producer seeks to compete by "undercutting" the price of a competitor by importing cheap goods in order to take a larger share of the market and thereby increase its profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to transfer production abroad, or to buy cheaply there, or to disappear.The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and therefore no responsibility for the unemployment it produces, the social expenditure of the state necessarily increases.
The situation is aggravated by the absolute unwillingness of businessmen to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage they have caused in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistics.
The ruthless practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies where the governments of individual countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments risk their own populations for private capital, regardless of social decline.
This is mainly reflected in the changes to existing laws.
The aim is to economically force its own population to accept the price dictate of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done both by a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and by restricting workers' rights in the area of labour law.
The result is growing poverty, along with an increase in the gap between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, there have been for many years public food dispensers for the poor who cannot make a living by their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
As part of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for well-employed people to receive such a wage that the state has to pay them to the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal was also made public in the case of auxiliary employees of the Bundestag.
The austerity measures of virtually all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation where people, under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in the social level, are forced to either emigrate as it was in the 19th century or to live on hunger wages on the margins of society in the hope that perhaps private investment capital will one day come to the country.
But the question is where does it come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, or Turkish, Moroccan, or Egyptian, or African still work for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media argue that the state cannot capitalize on its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic disaster.
The private equity firm insists that the state must not intervene in the economy by controlling interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not influence, now it actually directs politics and thus the whole state in its own egoistic sense.
The obvious answer is yes.
The proof is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, providing mutual benefits, legislation where practically everything is reprehensible but nothing criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that the state ministries for lack of funds commission the drafting of draft laws to private law firms, which are mostly connected with industry.
These bills are then approved in the Bundestag.
All power does not come from the people, as the constitutions of the Western type proclaim, but from financially strong groups preferring their own interests.
It is obvious that liberal-oriented democracies are now rapidly coming into the situation described by Appianus in his Crisis of the Roman Republic in the time of Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been in complete disarray and the authorities have occupied themselves by force.
For bribes, unlawful favors, and using stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption were rampant, and the people went to the polls with a pre-sold voice"... "characteristic people did not apply for office at all, so once as a result of this disruption the state was eight months without consuls"..... "It began to be said that the only cure in a bad situation was self-government, which had to be elected by an energetic man."
Conclusion As in ancient times, contemporary society is based on a ruthless preference for self-benefit, regardless of society-wide interest.
Private capital, by its very nature, is no longer capable of understanding and applying the benefits of society as a whole.
The result is now, as then, an unprecedented decadence of elites without any attempt at deeper reforms.
The causality of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current state, the demise of these systems in favor of liberal-type democracy can be considered as a kind of break with the expectation of the next round.
Especially disastrous is the fact that the present elites completely ignore the possible hundreds of thousands of lives lost in the future, humanitarian and social disasters that we are already witnessing along with crimes against humanity, as we know them from old and new history.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and the European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political-social reforms that will strengthen the state’s capital participation in the economy, strengthen the influence of citizens on the government, and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
