In November 1979, a mob of Islamist students seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohamed Reza Pahlavi, who fled to the US after the revolution, which had been the patron of his regime for several decades.
For the US administration, the situation did not offer a positive starting point - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as it would fundamentally threaten the confidence of allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages was not possible in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later exacerbated by a failure to free the hostages by force.
The diplomats were eventually released after 444 days of negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate at home has sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iran sentiment.
The debate in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film, directed by Ben Affleck Argo, describes one episode of that history that brought America a small victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six employees escaped from it.
They ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they went on Canadian passports as members of the film crew, which in the country surveyed locations for the shooting of science fiction large-scale film.
Combinations of genres
The plan, devised by "exfiltration" expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's cooperation.
To make the legend credible, the film project was reported in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a strange combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time the so-called "caper movie", the story of a successful piece, a set-up - an example can be a series of Danny's partners.
The film thus alternates moods - on the one hand documentary sequences from Tehran (in the title sequence are shown iconic contemporary photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were shown in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, light passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and slight exaggeration.
And then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable career restart.
The derided actor became a respected director, and even his acting ceased to be the subject of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime film Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller The City (2010).
At the same time, it is the first Affleck film not to take place in the director's home Boston.
The atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that elevated the director’s older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck also shows it in Argos, where Tehran “plays” Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, reconstructing real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which also conveys the emotion of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere out of the blue.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake crew at a Tehran bazaar).
Too many events in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the narrated story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of thrilling scenes.
He works quite successfully with it, sometimes he makes up his mind about reality - everything is not so elegant there anymore (the scene in which the impending crisis at Tehran airport is averted by a phone call in America and the chase on the runway seems quite far-fetched).
The weakness of Argos, however, is the distraction of having to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserve more space and are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck’s film is losing some of its dramatic thrust; it is a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciated for its realization and the retro style evoking the thrillers of the 1970s.
