Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The site www.bankovni feeky.com, which annually launches a survey about the most absurd bank fee, has now decided to launch a competition for "the most absurd regulations or ideas from the EU".
"We were led to this by the last event when the EU plans to adopt a 40% quota for women in the management of large European companies," said Patrik Nacher, the organizer of the poll.
Among the nominated absurdities, for example, is the recent decision of the European Court to unify the premium rates for men and women.
So far, women have been favoured in the price of life insurance policies because they are objectively less risky for insurance companies.
"Other incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The vote will then take place until the end of February 2013," Nacher said.
The controversial EU regulations include mandatory incorporation of biofuels into fuels, which is detrimental to nature, a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or a directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs significantly more expensive this year.
Criticism had previously also faced a de facto ban on the use of the term spread butter or the exclusion of incandescent bulbs from sale.
Good quality bananas should be 14 centimeters
The EU apparatus often makes decisions under the pressure of one or another business or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by some state or group of states (so the Czech Republic is now also enforcing the demands of its banks with the threat of a veto).
The lobby's interests were also behind the fact that, for example, bananas of the highest quality had to be at least 14 cm long in the Union and were not allowed to show "anomalous curvature".
The European Commission has defended itself by harmonising existing inconsistent national standards that have complicated trade.
Despite opposition from some countries, the EU has already softened the fruit and vegetable standards, pointing out that the existing directives lead to food waste.
A candidate for victory in the poll may also be last year's EU regulation, according to which it must be mandatory for the inflatable balloons sold to be warned that children under 8 years of age must not inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU has cited U.S. research that says balloons are the leading cause of death among children from choking.
Similar restrictions now apply to children up to the age of 14 when blowing in fairgrounds.
Curious ideas are born at home
The rule concerning European officials themselves is also quite absurd - everyone who has an official function in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia for Greece due to the sensitivity of the topic and must speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia) instead.
In addition to some of the above-mentioned absurdities, the Bank Fees.com server in cooperation with the association of liberal economists, Laissez Faire, has also nominated an EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a Member State.
The EU has set maximum volumes of food stocks that may have been located on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our entry into the Union.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the specified volumes for canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a high fine.
The organizers of the poll were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having the sea, and the idea of granting subsidies on request for subsidies.
These ideas, however, did not originate in Brussels, but in Prague.
"We are handicapped because we don't have the sea.
We will ask the European Union for a refund," said the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (Czech Social Democratic Party - ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he stated that a lot of grain was produced in our country and as a result of so-called intervention purchases, the state should have full warehouses, which he had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros for having the Czech Republic further to the ports.
The European Commission finally met the Czech Republic by organising a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The subsidy was offered to municipalities by the Ministry of Regional Development managed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), specifically to go to write a request for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are an exception
While regulations are easy to criticise in the Member States, EU efforts to regulate and, at the same time, to make the whole Union work more efficiently and develop deserve recognition, according to a number of experts.
For example, EU subsidies for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration, but which were forced by Member States in budgetary negotiations, are a more serious problem, according to experts.
Emotion among Czechs is also aroused by the fact that, like other countries of the Union, the Czech Republic has to fight in Brussels for the right to specific designation of its traditional products, and it does not always succeed in this match.
The Czechs, after a six-year struggle with the Germans and Austrians, defended the designation of Olomouc tvaruzky, but the domestic rum, whose tradition in our country dates back to the 19th century, had to be renamed to tuzemák.
Naming rum can only be carried by products from cane distillate, and not from sugar beet.
The official list of EU registered products includes the world-famous cheeses feta and gorgonzola, marzipan from Germany’s Lubeck region and Parma ham, such as Karlovy Vary biscuits, pohořelice and Třeboň carp and Žatec hops.
The EU trade mark can also be proud of Pardubice gingerbread and Hořice tubes.
