MVRDV Architects are proof that real adventures don't just happen in the head - for example, Spijkenisse and the recently built Mountain of Books - 2 images
"I find the building cheerful, it looks futuristic, and there's something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, who walks along the side of the road.
Stefan Spermon, IT technician at a nearby large company, thinks, "Of course, the house is nice."
I wonder why we still need a library.
They all have internet, iPads and e-books.
None of these old-style libraries are voluntary anymore, are they?
Spijkenisse, a housing estate in close proximity to Rotterdam without its own job opportunities that are not worth a visit, holds a special record.
With a population of 80,000, the municipality has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
To solve this stupid situation, a few years ago, the decision was made to contribute to general education and to build seven nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures of fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes.
However, the success of the educational campaign was not overwhelming.
And so the city councilors realized that there was only one way to become masters of statistics: we had to have a library!
Winy Maas of the MVRDV architectural studio in Rotterdam, master of insanely bold bar charts and maker of witty, often cynical structures, accepted the matter with the usual calm and appeared at the 2003 competition with five books under his arm and a smirk on his face.
And while the commission was still looking around in amazement and shrugging its shoulders, the brash Maas piled his gifts on top of himself by size and ended his activist speech with the words "Dear City Municipality!"
So this is my proposal for the Mountain of Books in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was piled up for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Mountain of Books was awarded the second place "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Small-town grey, which could not offer more than a post-modern pedestrian zone and an extraordinarily ugly town hall, behind the white facade of which you would expect a dairy, is richer in a bit of contemporary architecture.
Above all, however, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The Long Road to the Book
First impression: a reader's eldorado under the cheese lid.
Although the lift runs through the massif of the mountain, you will discover true spatial and reading passions only when climbing the topography on foot.
The glazed interior is bright and clear from all sides, the floor made of burnt fibreglass and the elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog and boys and girls playing football.
And books, books, books everywhere.
“Normally, bookshelves stand along the facade, and there’s a large dark space in the middle that’s mostly uncozy and impersonal,” says Winy Maas.
We built the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed the reader’s space from the inside out.
The interior of the Hill of Books is cleverly used: in the center there are offices, an internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and a house equipment exchange.
A special delight are the black book shelves, which are one wall covering, one window sill, and at other times a railing of stairs.
The appearance, structure and smell are foreign.
Even sworn architects and construction engineers shake their heads over unknown building materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials here,” says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipal council of Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard magazine.
So one day, in a Frisian farm, we came across a suitable agricultural waste product.
For many years, a millimetre fleece made of synthetic material has been used as a substrate under the roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It is cheap and time-efficient.
Thin textile lasts for one or two seasons and is then ripe to be thrown away in bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such quantity - was pressed onto boards four centimeters thick.
Due to heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and load-bearing material that smells a little like a new car and a little like sports shoes.
Take the 105 steps to get to the top.
At the end of your almost 500-meter journey, you will be rewarded not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and figs in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, but mainly about the correct humidity in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a new soul
“You probably wouldn’t believe it, but this house, despite its many glass surfaces, is a showcase project in terms of ecology,” Trouborst says.
It is heated and cooled by the earth's heat.
Although the Mountain of Books stands under a glass lid, the sun shines inside only briefly, even on sunny days.
Wide glued wooden trusses, which stand perpendicular to the glazed facade, serve as a shading and capture a large part of the sunlight.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest can handle fully automatic roller shutters.
Stefan Spermon, an early IT sceptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And traditional Chinese medicine teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who even calls Boekenberg the “long-awaited soul” of Spijkenisse.
The reason: every resident of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate one book from his personal fund.
At first, the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library, which currently has 70,000 pieces, were to be filled.
The concept has proven itself.
The shelves are completely full.
“There’s nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, everyone has a certain relationship with the new house.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which in professional jargon is called identity formation.
Spijkenisse wrote a history of literature.
No matter how young and uneducated he is.
This is ultimately the starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the decision to accept Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is teetering on the narrow edge of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: Germany signalled earlier this week that it would vote against a proposal for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
Berlin abstained from the vote.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza
Now, however, Germany must be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think he's going to support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
It was eventually adopted by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on serious international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason is that they are just changing their foreign policy, away from the US-controlled policy, so to speak, towards German foreign policy.
The situation is all the more difficult because Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
The Germans are on two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still settling into their role, but they are on the way to a more “normal” foreign policy.
The foreign policy they have in France or the UK.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean in German terms?
It shows readiness to take positions in the case of national interests that are independent of the positions of the US or European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers, and therefore Germany must protect her interests.
Did economic interests influence attitudes in the Middle East conflict and voting at the UN?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to scare away the public, but also the elites in the Arab countries.
That plays a role anyway.
But I wouldn’t want to give too much importance to it either, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
In any case, this plays an important role in German thinking.
Did it damage Germany’s relations with the US when Germany abstained in both important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe and even in the USA there is a great understanding of the German position.
That is why I do not think it was as dramatic a turning point as it was in Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect from it.
This signals that he must be considered an international player and his interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States is clearly in favour of a veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of American internal politics.
I think the Obama administration probably has a deep understanding of the European position.
However, due to the political situation there, this position cannot, of course, be held publicly.
I think the differences of opinion are not at all as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and with the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes it difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would have been a little easier for the Germans if there had been a coherent and united European policy, which is not happening at the moment.
Therefore, they cannot be part of a broader line and must instead drive things forward from their own position.
That’s what they do with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take a leading role in the future and will push Europe towards a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player? Does it even want to take on the lead role?
Or is leadership still difficult for Germany?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still unpleasant, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult for this country to play a larger role.
For example, if we look at the European crisis, every time Germany takes on a larger role, anti-German sentiment is created.
This does not make it easier for the Germans.
It's actually an old problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be acceptable to all sorts of neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
The influence of the US in European politics is now steadily decreasing, but the EU is not currently filling this vacuum. Who else is left here?
The Germans will have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it makes them uncomfortable and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly study the challenges of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German policy, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
