Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, military prosecutor says
The military prosecutor is trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations of abusive treatment in custody.
The hearing focuses on Manning's stay in military custody in the town of Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed on the basis of Manning's abusive treatment in prison.
He is accused of stealing thousands of documents.
The military prosecutor is trying to prove that Private Bradley Manning, who is accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, missed many opportunities to complain about the abusive treatment he allegedly suffered in military custody.
The military prosecutor, Maj. Ashden Fein, cross-examined Private Manning at a preliminary hearing in Ft. Maede, Maryland, claimed that records of weekly visits Manning had with unit officers over the course of nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination, which took place during a hearing conducted at the request of the defence to dismiss a case brought against Manning on grounds of ill-treatment during the period of detention, which is itself a sufficient punishment, took place the day after Manning testified that he had contemplated suicide while in custody.
An army intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while serving in Iraq.
The material was then posted online on WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of its information.
At Friday's hearing, military prosecutor Fein and Manning went through forms that officers filled out after meeting Manning at Quantico's detention center, where he was held under heightened security from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When asked about these forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the overall treatment at the facility as "very professional".
Forms do not show any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly asked Manning how he was being treated, Fein claimed.
Manning replied that he had expressed concerns about various problems orally and that the officers who visited him had spoken to him about these concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not record these problems.
"They wrote down 'no problems' (after discussing the concerns) and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't mention them," Manning said.
Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment of himself in January 2011 in a meeting with a commission assessing suicidal thoughts, which he had expressed several months earlier in the form.
Manning responded that during this meeting, his intention was to achieve a reduction in the "injury prevention" regime.
The military said it used this restrictive regime (one level below the suicide watch) for its protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the guards in custody to know that I was okay and that I wanted to cancel this injury prevention regime ... so that I could enjoy the increased quality of life that I saw," Manning said.
Manning testified on Thursday of his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transported to a detention facility at Marine Corps Base in Quantico, Virginia in July 2010.
He said he was considering suicide in Kuwait, and one time he fainted because of the heat.
He stated that the fact that he was not allowed to know what would happen to him and what was happening in the outside world was very disheartening.
"My world has shrunk only to the base of Arifjan, to that cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Manning stated that after arriving at Quantico, he spent most of the days (at least 21 hours, but often longer than 23 hours) in a small cell without any company.
Manning said he was only allowed one mattress, a blanket, slippers, some clothes and glasses.
He said he was trying to walk because sleeping or just lying down during the day was against regulations.
Manning said he always slept with the light on the outside of the cell in his eyes.
He stated that if the guards could not see his face when he turned the other way at night, they woke him up and had to turn back.
Manning's attorney filed a formal complaint about the treatment of Private Manning in January 2011.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
On Friday, Judge Manning was also asked about the charges he made in Thursday's deposition, relating that after being forced to sleep one night in his cell in Quantico naked, he was also forced to stand naked in front of guards and other fellow prisoners in the morning count.
Manning testified that he was not allowed to cover himself with his blanket while counting.
In a Friday hearing conducted by Judge Manning, he stated that he had decided, by order of his guards, that he had a blanket to cover himself with, but admitted that no one had given him the order to postpone it.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night because he tried to show the officer that he was not dangerous.
Manning stated that he told the officer that he could use a belt from his underwear or his slippers to hurt himself, but he did not.
Manning testified that his underwear, his slippers, and his glasses were removed from his cell that night.
His lawyer hopes that the judge will take into account his experience during his imprisonment and that if he is convicted before a military court, which is expected to begin at the beginning of next year, he will significantly reduce his sentence.
The defense said it plans to plead guilty to lower crimes and that it will fight the other charges because they are too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to begin this week, with the military prosecutor expected to defend the detention conditions as justified.
The Pentagon said in a statement that Manning was held in accordance with regulations regarding all detainees held in maximum security custody.
The charges against Manning include aiding the enemy, illegally causing intelligence documents to be posted on the Internet, transmitting information related to national security, and stealing public property or records.
If he is convicted on all counts, he can be sentenced to life imprisonment.
