However, there are reasons to believe that this can interrupt their deadly stalemate.
A war that is neither won nor lost.
At first glance, there seems to be little reason for optimism.
Even if the cease-fire on November 21 lasts, the fighting this week has boosted hawks on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamic movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to retreat even though Gaza has suffered defeat.
Despite the killing of several Hamas leaders and the closure of 1.7 million Gazans in one of the most deplorable and populous corners of the planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining influence in the West Bank, another piece of Palestine that is currently run by its staunch rivals from Fatah, a more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, Hamas leaders can very well conclude that time is on their side.
