Australia's ugly tobacco and cigarette packaging laws, the first of their kind in the world, came into force, replacing the brand's logos and colors with generic olive-green boxes featuring hideous images of sick body parts and images of babies and newborns ill from smoking their parents.
In addition to various health warnings and pictures, the only mandatory difference between the boxes are the brand names printed in the same small print.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government says the goal is to discourage young people from smoking by depriving it of its appeal.
Studies show that if people don’t start smoking by age 26, there’s a 99% chance they’ll never start smoking.
“Even with very young children, you can see that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to sell them with their product,” says federal health minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown in the logo with the idea of being a princess.
While Australia has one of the lowest numbers of smokers in the world, and changes will have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are considering introducing similar measures.
The tobacco industry has lobbied hard against the introduction of these laws.
Tobacco companies have argued that this law will increase black market trading, leading to cheaper and more affordable cigarettes.
“There will be serious unintended consequences from this legislation,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring many more of these products, which will be sold on Australian streets.
Others say the law has increased their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, said the demand for silicone cigarette packaging used to hide disgusting boxes had increased from near-zero sales two months ago when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost their appeal over laws to Australia's Supreme Court.
