After a number of Australian laws banning television advertising, sponsoring sporting events, and demanding that most retailers hide cigarettes from direct view, tobacco marketing has moved online.
Australia has banned online advertising by local companies and websites, but cannot restrict foreign sites.
“If you’re a tobacco industry marketer and only have this little space left to promote your products, online space is an unbeatable place for you to be,” says Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Ms. Freeman noted an increase in ratings of brands on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, carried out by "average Honza".
We have to ask, is it just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and took the job of creating this video, or is there a marketing company involved?
British American Tobacco Australia argues that the industry has focused on how it will handle the new regulations rather than marketing.
The industry has gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras, and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations - countries within the World Trade Organization declare that trade is unfairly restricted, despite the fact that none of the countries trade significantly with Australia.
The SOO decision is expected in mid-2013.
Minister Plibersek says the government has held talks with other governments considering similar laws on packaging.
