In a world of constant connection is not so bad to be bored
The last Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane was in mechanical trouble and we had to wait for the next plane to arrive.
So I had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I won't lie to you.
Waiting half a day at the airport for the next flight is pretty annoying, despite the distraction of books, magazines and an iPhone (not to mention duty-free stores).
But some scientists and child development experts are increasingly coming up with the praise of boredom.
They say it’s good for us (and our kids) to get bored sometimes.
It forces the brain to go in interesting directions, which can promote creativity.
And since most of us are constantly connected to a screen these days, we don’t have a chance to enjoy the boredom.
Should we encourage boredom?
Yeah.
And no.
But I'll come back to that.
First, like many people, I assumed that boredom was a relatively new phenomenon that occurred with the advent of more leisure time.
But as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, says, he is the author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011).
"In fact, boredom has a long history," he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription concerning boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there is the question of how we define boredom.
The difficulty is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After viewing the research literature and presenting the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience "I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I wasn't able to do it".
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says there's no compulsion to do anything about apathy.
He says that the core of boredom is "disrupting the process of attention, associated with a bad mood and a sense of slowly passing time."
Being bored can be a lot like being depressed.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship with each other, bored people tend to see the problem as an environment or world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re bored when we’re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study, “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” published in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science in September, Professor Eastwood and colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape to which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group could not hear it at all.
Those who heard the TV program quietly reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but they weren't sure why and attributed the difficulty to boredom.
When trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, attention deficit disorder can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, “like finding the wrong parts on a factory line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored.”
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and doodling, which is often viewed as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight boredom and keep people physically more attentive.
"Research shows that children who are allowed to fidget learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still," said Professor Fenske.
We've all been bored at times - the delay of my flight, the humming speaker, the particularly lengthy film.
But some individuals are more likely to be bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists developed the Boredom Proneness Scale in the 1980s.
The scale includes questions such as: "Many things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous," and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all.".
Using these scales, the researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulations.
Teenagers, however, are generally indifferent.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teens reported being bored at school and doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know if the percentage of boredom would be higher or lower now, 21 years later.
But he said he knows “adolescence is the peak time for boredom,” which is largely due to the fact that children and youth are not given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question: "Is boredom good for you?".
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, gamble or abuse addictive substances as a way to alleviate it.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have discussed the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
“Boredom is your brain’s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” said Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at NYU.
But the brain doesn’t always know the best thing to do.
If you get bored and use this energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not for a long time.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will not be bored anymore, but he will not learn how to entertain himself or drive himself, said Professor Fenske.
And "this self-management is transferred from one situation to another," the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain himself, but will gain more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we really want to celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of it.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are away from the constant rattling of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
"We accuse it of needing to be bored even more, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful," he said.
What people are really looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy their free time.
"In an environment in which we are constantly overstimulated," he said, "it's hard to find ways to entertain ourselves when the noise turns off."
There is no manual on the new marijuana law in Colorado.
Nineteen-year-old Anthony Orozco, a college student and soccer player from southeastern Colorado, is facing criminal charges for what will soon be legal across the state for possession of several grams of marijuana and the pipe he used to smoke her.
Mr. Orozco said that one day in September he was driving with several friends in Lamar, on the plains near the border with Kansas, when he was stopped.
After a police officer found marijuana in his car, Mr. Orozco was issued a subpoena for possession of drugs and equipment to use drugs - minor offenses that cost $100 for each fine - and was given a court date.
"They treated us like criminals," Mr Orozco said.
But is he a criminal?
In the uncertain weeks following Colorado's vote to legalize small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the response to hundreds of minor drug cases depends on the location rather than the law.
Hundreds of marijuana offenses have already been dropped here and in the state of Washington, which has passed similar measures.
The police department has stopped blaming adults aged 21 and older for holding a small amount that will be legally allowed after the law enters into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado's more conservative precincts have stated that they will continue with existing marijuana cases, and still blame people for possession.
At the same time, several cities in the suburbs of Denver are voting to prevent the opening of new, state-licensed marijuana stores in their municipalities.
"This thing is going so fast, I don't know what's going to happen next," said Daniel J. Oates, a police chief in the city of Aurora, east of Denver.
Even the regulators in Washington state are scratching their heads.
And they are looking for guidance on how to set up a licensing system for cultivation, production, distribution and sales - all by December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and now recreational.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide," said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Licensing Council.
But as Mr Smith admitted, no place or system can do more than suggest what might work.
“There is no real precedent to follow,” he said.
The Washington I-502 Act comes into effect on December 6, which also leaves an annual vacuum during which there will not yet be a state licensing system, but legal possession does.
And there are tricky mechanical issues that need to be resolved during this time, such as how to balance the state's "adequate access" directive to licensed marijuana with its ban on the trade of cannabis within 330 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds or children's centers.
“Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently established research group.
On November 21, Aurora Police Chief Oates sent an email to his officers announcing that the city's prosecutor would no longer prosecute violations for possession of small amounts of marijuana by any citizen over 21 and that police would "effectively" stop blaming people for these crimes.
Chief Oates said police would enforce city laws regulating medical marijuana growers and would continue to prosecute drug traffickers and dealers.
In Weld County, northern Colorado, district attorney Ken Buck presents a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mostly as a way to pressure users to seek treatment.
Currently, 119 people face charges of possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them face additional charges.
"Our office is required to prosecute criminal offences that were criminal offences at the time they occurred," Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The response was complicated even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county's largest city, no longer blame adults for holding small amounts.
The district attorney, Pete Hautzinger, supports this decision, but has also decided not to dismiss all pending possession cases.
"I don't think I'm wasting my time continuing to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana into the hands of the government and the legal system will never be easy.
And conflicting reactions across the state have revealed a deep ambivalence among local officials with regard to this large-scale state green experiment.
For district attorneys, this is a "cultural barrier," said Sean McAllister, a lawyer from Denver who represents the defendants for possession of marijuana, and a local spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
"They've spent so much of their lives prosecuting people that they still can't really accept that it's legal," he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are well on their way to becoming national test cases for the legalization of the drug.
Advocates and state authorities are planning new boundaries for legalized marijuana sales while anxiously awaiting instructions from the federal government, which still plans to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Proponents of marijuana legalization hope the Justice Department will bow.
Despite several arrests of medical marijuana sellers and patients using it, the federal government has mostly left medical marijuana stores in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states in operation.
While anti-drug agents are unlikely to break down the door to intercept a small bag of the drug, they are likely to resist allowing state-regulated recreational marijuana deals allowed by new laws, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former adviser to the Obama administration's anti-drug policy.
Several Colorado cities are not waiting for federal authorities to proceed.
Even before election day, some local governments approved a moratorium on any new marijuana business, though it will be about a year before any store can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose proposed a six-month ban, and it is likely to come into effect next week.
"We don't want to be in a situation where we license someone and then we have a big federal issue," said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We are looking at what the community voted for, versus what the state voted for.
There's really a lot of questions.
Petronella Wyatt: "I was forced to leave Oxford because I'm a Conservative".
It is not only today’s students who are attacked for their opinions.
I don't remember ever dreaming of studying at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother studied at a university that I thought was the world’s largest seat of knowledge, a modern wrapped Greek symposium motivating two pillars of civilization, freedom of thought and tolerance.
And so far, in the late 1980s, within two weeks of joining Worcester College, where I wanted to study history, I packed my bags and plunged into the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I gave up because I objected to the students making love in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson famously stated that I left because I was forced to drink from battered mugs.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was subject to systematic bullying and intimidation.
Not because of my rather bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one reason, and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a high-ranking adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
You may ask why I'm only bringing it up now.
Simply because recent reports suggest that a new generation of students to the right of the center suffer from similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred against conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of these students claimed the same protections of equal rights as gays, people with disabilities and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Younger Years Association (JCR) at Corpus Christi College argue that because of their political views, they are "often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks, and shown that they are not welcome".
They call for the creation of a position on the University Equal Opportunities Committee to ensure that they are free to express their views.
Their situation was not helped by the recently launched BBC Two documentary programme Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right, which portrayed the Conservatives as oddballs and neo-Nazis.
The show featured graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who rode Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit, and had a cane with a silver head.
At other colleges, conservative students say they are being treated like "victim lambs" because of the introduction of higher tuition.
Luke Black, a 20-year-old vice president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told a Sunday newspaper that "left-wing influence in universities is growing.
People think we're like the Bullingdon Club without them meeting us at all."
A 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi, Samuel Roberts, who is behind the movement for greater protection, says such a climate is "unpleasant," while 19-year-old elected OUCA president Stephanie Cherill says there has been a deterioration in the attitude of JCR members toward people to the right of Wednesday.
"This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual debate as well as to members' well-being," he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford, I was a minority of one member.
I joined in September 1986, 18-year-old and cripplingly shy.
The hatred for the Conservative Party was the most bitter.
A year earlier, the university had voted to refuse to award an honorary degree to former student Margaret Thatcher due to cuts in funding for higher education.
Even Stalinists would be apprehensive about the atmosphere.
During the first few days of the opening week, when the new students were interacting with each other and with the professors, I got to taste the wormwood that was to come.
I have found that not only do professors tacitly approve of the teasing of conservative pupils, but they gladly participate in it.
A policy of mining strike, privatization and government resistance to sanctions against apartheid in South Africa was brought to the wood-clad auditoriums.
My first talk was about translating an 18th-century French text into English, and I wasn’t prepared for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I was pretty good at it.
Professor Pitt, a little man with a face like a cake dough, was very gall.
"Do the Thatchers refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked.
The other students sniggered.
There were tears in my eyes.
"I suggest you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, unless you're too busy with social matters," Professor Pitt snarled.
I went back to my room in disarray.
At dinner at school, I was sitting alone when I felt a slight tap on my shoulder.
He was a second-year student named James, who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
Unfortunately, that's the case.
Anyone suspected of conservatism is a target.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be even worse for you.
Most conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour.
Later, at the local pub, I cowardly tried to pretend.
I insisted I didn't agree with everything Thatcher said.
This trick proved unsuccessful.
A first-year student of philosophy, politics, and economics who (what an irony) went to Eton said, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're infected.
The other students talked to him.
I was sick, dirty.
"How do conservatives love each other?" one asked.
They're hitting each other, aren't they?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the liberal legislation of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Would I have to change into a Labour and suppress my natural inclinations?
For three years, they developed before me as a purgatory of ignorance and isolation.
The only openly conservative professor was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history who resided at my faculty.
He was hated not only for being conservative, but also for being Margaret Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of those who write speeches to her.
He was almost there.
He hated the place for its provinciality and pettiness, and for its tendency toward a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he took up the position of professor at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began commuting from Oxford to my parents’ home in London, seeking refuge with my disinterested metropolitan friends and family.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He couldn't believe it.
During his studies at Oxford in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said pathetically.
They wouldn't do that, not in a city of dreamy mood.
Even my communist friends have always had perfect manners.
His wet eyes were drenched.
Try again.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by frequent trips to London, my emotional endurance deteriorated.
My friend, also a supporter of the Conservative Party, succumbed to pressure and gave up his convictions.
The following week, in the course of teaching, when another professor of history declared in complete seriousness that I was an "enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Even though I blushed with shame inside, I confessed to having been “brainwashed by my parents” and called them “old fools.”
The relief was short-term.
The nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was hammered by my father.
At the time, he was writing two columns for Murdoch's newspaper every week.
My door was locked.
I shuffled inside and after five minutes my pursuers gave up.
After they left, I packed my suitcase and caught the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a snot-nosed wimp.
But no 18-year-old girl or boy should be subject to such intimidation and poison in an educational institution.
Even more tragic, it was Oxford that not only produced 14 conservative prime ministers, but that also hides to this day behind the undeserved reputation of a place with equality and freedom of thought.
