World's Hardest Craft: Sulfur Carriers in the Kawah Ijen Volcano
For four euros, carriers in the Indonesian volcano area gamble with their life and health as they lay 70 kilos of sulfur down steep stone trails.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by mining sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, they have to dig to the bottom of the crater every day, where sulfur gases escape from the interior of the Earth and pass into a solid state upon contact with air.
After cutting large blocks of sulfur, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, he carries them off on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
To the summit of the volcano, which rises 2,386 meters, it is only 250 meters, but it takes the exhausted carriers over 40 minutes to climb at a turtle pace, because they maintain balance and carefully consider their steps so that they do not slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any stumble could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell from the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine
When they are up, they make their way around the tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and tired of carrying the heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilo of sulfur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has its place in everyday life and is used for making matches, fun pyrotechnics, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
“Because we normally carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip,” explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and is ruined at the end, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) per day.
While this seems like a negligible amount for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the field.
"The daily wage of miners is very high here. For example, for collecting coffee you pay 15 000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day, and the salary in a fortnight is 2 million rupees (167 euros)," explains the bearer, who previously worked on the tourist island of Bali as a bricklayer.
There was his salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) per day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as compelling in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali who is Hindu, and I took her to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto has asthma, he's breathing hard, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Anto risks his life three times a day in the volcano Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll on him, despite his face being protected by a special mask and glasses.
He's got asthma, he's breathing hard, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases escaping from the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
“I’m going to work for two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than decent English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man, beset by fate, could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, and instead do the work of a porter.
It shares a filthy wooden hut with other porters and wakes up at 2 a.m. every day, as sulfur continues to bubble up at night and its characteristic yellow colour turns blue and glows in the dark.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto climbs into the crater and lights his way with a small flashlight attached to his helmet and bought it himself with his money.
About 400 carriers are carrying sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Although the company has a high income, it did not mechanize sulfur mining because of cost savings, nor does it provide any equipment to carriers working on their own and with such effort.
In fact, they don’t even get a share of the 30,000 rupees ($2.5) of the photography surcharge that, along with a 15,000 rupee ($1.2) ticket, the park’s guardians choose from tourists who come to take pictures of the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for cattle, not people,” said Madrusin, a 42-year-old heavy carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for three decades.
He can lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he will keep working "as long as possible" because he needs money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life.
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes, when the wind unexpectedly turns and catches the miners in the thick fumes that come out of the volcano, the miners are so claimed that none of them complain that they suffer from serious diseases... but this is evident from their frequent respiratory problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and wounds on the shoulders caused by the weight of the baskets.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can only load 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his colleagues dig up 15 tons of sulfur in a volcano, which three trucks then take on a steep path between the thickets to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life," Unainik said, opening his mouth wide, missing several teeth.
Of his five sons, the eldest, a 30-year-old, also earns by mining sulfur.
Time passes, but the constant misery of one of the world's heaviest crafts persists from generation to generation - the crafts performed by human mules at Kawah Iljen.
Singapore Seeks Babies to Save the Economy
Singaporeans are seduced by the fact that they do not have children, for careers, stress and the cost of living and education.
"Singapore's population needs to grow".
I'm married and I'm a patriot, you're my wife and you're a patriot.
It may seem incredible that this slogan is part of a menthol candy ad, but nevertheless - or perhaps because of it - the video went viral on YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
These sentences are part of a rap that uses local "put a bun in the oven" cues as a mockery of Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency that created the video, hopes the ad will draw attention to the problem in a humorous way.
The agency's artistic director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the influence of music to make people fulfill "their civic duty".
“It’s all about the internet, so it must have been fun and funny.
This is the country's biggest problem.
We are the worst in the world in the reproduction of our population, so we felt it was a topic we had to touch on.
We knew that the government was trying to do a lot of things, like expand perfumes with pheromones or organize introduction parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but not fully functional.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing possible, like making a rap, to solve this problem."
1.2 children
The one who doesn't take it too lightly is the Singaporean government.
They spend $1,300 a year encouraging citizens to have more children.
The government's marriage and family package provides up to $15,000 per child, extending maternity leave, and allocating financial benefits.
However, all these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy city-state with advanced technology in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservatism and strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore with respect to stratification of the population is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded 2, which is considered a recovery rate, was in 1976.
Why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Department of the National Population Authority, says this is due to "better education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
“People have a wider range of choices when it comes to life goals and priorities, not just marriage and family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of single people and to the postponement of marriage and childbearing, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
While there were efforts under immigration policy to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a measure against population declines, this caused resentment among local residents.
Some Singaporean websites show undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and making little effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party recorded its worst election result since independence began last year.
After the elections, there was an effort to solve the problem using quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the decline in birth rates has known effects on national economic growth, tax revenues, health spending, and immigration policy, there have also been some unexpected consequences for Singapore.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to affect the real estate business.
The Urban Development Authority has begun to regulate the number of small apartments known as "boot boxes" that can be built in certain urban zones.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have had great success in sales.
However, there is concern that these apartments may support a bachelor lifestyle and discourage developers from building large single-family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of the development firm EL Developers, says their "bootboxes" are selling much faster than larger homes.
“They’re more popular, so they sell days to weeks faster than larger homes.
That’s why they’re much better for our cash flow.”
However, it admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed out
Singapore is a city-state.
Although these new rules could lead to an increase in the nation’s birth rate, a conversation with Singaporeans working in the city’s financial district suggests they won’t have much of an effect.
“People are still stressed, houses are expensive, as is education, which is why many people put it off,” says the young official.
“Let others have children.
But for me it is important to rely on my own money and time," says another, about twenty years old, a young man.
Both men and women mention careers, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how much the government tries to force its citizens to have children, it is Singaporeans who have the final say on starting a family.
What is private offline is private and online
Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something of a personal nature or an “area of private life that everyone has the right to protect themselves against any disruption”.
What is privacy for people under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers to which he is exposed when he publishes things on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy to be "something entirely of its own" on a personal level and a "username and password" when it came to social networks.
“I wouldn’t reveal my biggest secret,” said ten-year-old Jorge in an effort to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"They're very secret secrets, my mom can know about them, but not the whole world," she says.
"On FB, I put nice pictures or pictures of how we play.
I also talk to acquaintances.
I wouldn’t share a photo that wasn’t mine or a photo that would ridicule someone,” she says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to post obscene photos, nude photos or crime photos, or to write humiliating or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
“I created a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don’t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there,” he adds.
“Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or communicate quickly with friends,” he says.
Without hesitation, he says, he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn't even care if someone recommended a stranger to him.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and admits he doesn’t know 20 people on his friends list.
“I’m not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
According to this boy, none of them had any clues or asked for his address or phone number.
“If I’m being pressured or required to do so, I’ll simply remove them from my account,” she admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading the recommendations on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to what is now called cyberbullying.
"A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
They threatened him and demanded money.
“He never knew who it was,” she confirms.
The victim did not log out of the account, according to José.
"You just activated the private mode."
It then explains a series of steps to set up your account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post pictures of acquaintances in awkward or awkward situations.
"Of course I would if someone bothered me or I just wanted to.
“It’s cyberbullying,” he said.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that for children and adolescents to navigate social networks properly, they need to understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
He states that: "The Internet originated as a means of seeking information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed."
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of education at Yale University and author of Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
"Digital natives are children and young people who were born in the era of this technology.
We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them and yet we are still learning,” he says.
He explains that this is a complex topic, "because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet ripe for it."
Also, to be prudent, in terms of surroundings, at a time when what they most desire is to be liked, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences,” he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and teens what privacy is is by asking questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do something doesn’t work,” he adds.
Next, Marielos Porras lists some of the options: There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Would you like someone to post your picture as you posted your friend’s?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you tag people in party photos, did you ask for their permission?
And one more thing: Do they all need to know what you’re doing?
The next point is to make them aware that they must behave in the Internet environment as well as outside it.
It's the same rules.
"A person outside the Internet is governed by respect, morality and other principles, and the same should be the case on social networks," he says.
Supervision
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, teacher in the first grade and educational advisor, explains that it is essential that parents of children carefully read the rules of social networks.
“If they understand every trick, they have a good basis for talking to children about the consequences of setting up an online account.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published,” he says.
Guardia is of the opinion that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of "don't talk to strangers".
