AIDS victims are now the result of a late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if a lightning bolt had struck me," he recounts, recalling a moment of truth that the doctor had tried to "somewhat mitigate" but apparently without success.
The boy kept it a secret from the family.
He decided to take his illness on his own and began to learn about it, with such dedication that he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the most ancient patients of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), to which he came in 1994 after several struggles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 1990s, when there were a lot of doubts, few treatment options, and more stigma.
At the time, even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) did not say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut."
At the time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their disease and come only after the virus has caused destruction of the organism and weakened the immune system, and then become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since the onset of AIDS, or at least the first documented cases, “means a great success that the life expectancy of a patient who starts treatment in a timely and appropriate manner is exactly the same as that of healthy people,” said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at Civil Hospital in Guadalajara, adding that this information was confirmed in a prestigious scientific publication in April this year.
HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that researchers have concluded that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and a full life depends on the degree of disability of the immune system of patients who are diagnosed with the disease, while those who do not use drugs are better off: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years, and people with 500 CD4 cells up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that someone who is diagnosed with HIV at age 25 can live without problems “while adhering to treatment until age 75,” the doctor explained in an interview.
To highlight this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, from 6,678 AIDS deaths in Mexico in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (United Nations Joint Programme on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that 60 percent of patients have died since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 so far this May. However, since 2005, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured.
Why do people continue to die from the disease?
“I think the problem is not access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it happens at the hospital.
The problem is that patients are coming in at a very advanced stage because they don't know the state of the disease, or late in the disease."
"Nine out of ten patients come when an associated infection is present. The only thing that needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose the disease sooner, and that's why we need to offer tests on a large scale to detect the disease to all those who ask for it."
His proposal coincides with specialists and officials from the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco and directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to get tested in a private laboratory just because his friend did, and despite his young age, he has already developed AIDS and also suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
“Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to know anything else.
“If I’m going to die, I’d rather have fun three times a week,” they say, but that’s not my case.
The change was for the better, I eat healthily, I exercise, I take medication."
To this day, all his parents know is that he suffered from cancer.
“I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I take care of myself and the other person," Fabrizio, who has taken up the call to share his experience with the daily MILENIO JALISCO, to motivate those who are afraid with his testimony today on World AIDS Day.
"Let them take tests. If they took risks, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, it's better. And if they have already been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like anyone else if they are responsible."
This message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a huge gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara-based journalist who is researching information about HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, “the distribution of condoms has really increased, they used to give us one or two, now they give us packages and hundreds of condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who don’t have access to condoms,” he said.
Among the most susceptible to new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want it for?" is a common question full of irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy employees, and medical staff that teens want to avoid, a reporter says.
He suggested changing this inefficient distribution, so that condoms are not just behind the counters, but the hundred are in dispensers in public restrooms, places that young people often go to.
“It’s not about promiscuity.
Nor is it a question of "paying for a beer and a motel," as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if he would agree to a condom distribution in his district.
That's not sexuality. It's best to make condoms available to those who are already leading a sex life," he noted.
Key figures in Jalisco
There were 13,435 cases (12,158 AIDS cases and 1,317 HIV cases).
In Mexico, it ranks fourth in new and detected AIDS cases and 13th in HIV-related cases.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% via the blood and 2% via the perinatal route.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are four to five people for every registered case who are unaware of the disease.
The ruling, passed by the U.S. Court of Appeals, which does not recognize Grupo Vitro’s debt restructuring mandated by bankruptcy in Mexico, sets a bad precedent for any national business with branches in a neighboring country and a solvency problem.
Thus, the procedures for restructuring firms allowed by Mexican law do not seem to apply in the land of streaks and stars despite international agreements.
Judge Harlin Hale's June 15 ruling at the North Texas bankruptcy court leaves Mexican firms defenseless against the possibility of confiscating their assets on the other side of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door to the U.S. Supreme Court to Mexico's main glass producer, citing three irregularities.
To begin with, while the judge of this case claims that creditors are to abide by United States insolvency law, the New Orleans-based Fifth District Court of Appeals says that the main procedure provides for bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
First, it would show ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational enterprises.
Essentially, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Commercial Law was created to this end, which is appointed by the arbiter to the organization of the American Law Institute.
Secondly, the judgment states that without the voting of branches from the internal corporate structure, whereby the debt of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognised, the required majority would not have been reached for the approval of the restructuring.
However, Mexican law allows for this possibility.
