Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, was world-renowned for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." on the television series Dallas, in which he embodied a man who acted recklessly and was insidious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the television series Dallas became a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. in this year’s new season of Dallas, died Friday afternoon of complications from cancer, according to the family’s official announcement to The Associated Press by the Dallas Warner Bros. production company.
"Larry returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he loved most," the family said in a statement.
Larry's family and his closest friends were in Dallas with him on Thanksgiving Day.
"Linda Gray, who played his wife in both the original and new series, was with Hagman the moment he died in Dallas hospital," said Hagman's agent Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
