Begins a course that explores the "end of the world"
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to do a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew it was an irresistible lure: The end of the "long number" of the Mayan calendar, due on December 21, caught many people as proof that the end of the world was coming.
Charmé, however, had no idea what awaited him in the next few months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the budget gap that some call “the debt Armageddon,” and the growing conflict in which Israel is drawn, the place where, according to Christians theorizing about the end of the world, the Apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charme told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey this week.
When we discuss what is happening in the world today, as if we have 30 days left, it is a really good time.
And remember, bad means good for the apocalyptic mind.
And this is not the only professor who offers courses on the "end of the world" in this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker holds a course on "Means, Culture, and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
“We discuss why these ideas expand over time,” he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that drive certain human behavior.
For example, if nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, war could break out.
This month, students are analyzing films with apocalyptic themes and exploring how they differ from real-life examples.
“I’ve been trying to inform students about what’s possible, probable, believable, and impossible,” says Vacker.
On the main campus of the State University of Pennsylvania, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, came together to organize a course with the simple title The End of the World.
"We don't connect '2012' because we always count on the possibility of re-arranging the course if the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "threatening doom," students must study, create projects, and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be held on the eve of the Apocalypse, giving students no choice but to work "just until the evening of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
"It stretched out into two hours," Restall said of his course for high-average students, 35 of whom applied.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we received e-mails asking if there was still room.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,” said 23-year-old Bridgid Robinson, a student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University in Camden.
Thus, apocalyptic, worldly, or religious thinking is only a matter of consolation or lack thereof.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class before in which it could be taught," he said.
"I'm enjoying it."
But no student interviewed, let alone a professor, said he believed in the end date of December 21.
“Our first project was about the Mayan prediction, and in a way, we’re refuting it,” said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior student at Temple University in West Chester.
"The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key point in the calendar," Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that goes back several centuries as people react to changes in their surroundings by predicting the end of the world.
This speculation is caused by the internet.
“Otherwise people don’t think about it,” he said.
This happens in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who lectures in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew of a course there on “the end of the world.”
"Philippines do not participate in the end of the world," he wrote, hinting at an exception at the highest office.
We have mercy on the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many days of final judgment, and said that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that December 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will perish.
Dates are taken lightly by both students and professors.
Several said they intend to go to the "end of the world" festivities.
“I think I’m going to call a few friends to laugh together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
